From 9e30f44c3a2bf84435c9f9c7360110e9989f6a7c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: David Vernet <void@manifault.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 13:28:12 -0500
Subject: [RFC PATCH 1/2] prctl: extend PR_SET_THP_DISABLE to optionally treat
 anon VMAs as advised

A process can opt out of THP with prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE), but there
is no per-process opt *in*.  A supervisor that wants one process to
receive MADV_HUGEPAGE-equivalent treatment for its whole anonymous
address space today has only bad options: modify the program
(impossible for a third-party binary), interpose every allocator call
from a shim (fragile, and cannot cover future mappings), or flip the
global policy to always (which imposes synchronous-compaction latency
on every process on the system -- exactly why the default is madvise).
process_madvise() does not help either: process_madvise_remote_valid()
deliberately excludes MADV_HUGEPAGE for remote mms, and MADV_COLLAPSE
is one-shot, doing nothing for the future faults of a growing heap.

The motivating workload is a game launcher opting in a third-party
game binary.  Factorio 2.0 headless on a Steam Deck runs a
memory/TLB-bound update loop: IPC 0.38, dTLB-load-misses 73.4%, with
only 18.5% of its 154 MB anon heap hugepage-backed (28.6 MB
AnonHugePages) under enabled=madvise, because the game's allocator
never issues MADV_HUGEPAGE.  Aggressive global THP settings drop
dTLB-load-misses to 22.8% (52x fewer absolute misses) and ran the
benchmark ~10% faster in an exploratory single-shot probe of that
broader global configuration (uncontrolled; the controlled interleaved
A/B in patch 2 puts the aggressive-khugepaged ceiling at +5.76%),
confirming heap TLB pressure is the lever -- but only this process
should pay for that treatment.

Commit 9dc21bbd62ed ("prctl: extend PR_SET_THP_DISABLE to optionally
exclude VM_HUGEPAGE") enumerated exactly this use case as its scenario
(4): "Stay at 'madvise' system policy, but enable THPs even when not
advised for selected workloads -- 'always' policy."  It also drew a
clear line: "a simple enable/disable is not really suitable for the
future, so we're not willing to add completely new toggles."  This
patch takes that line seriously: it adds no new toggle and no new
prctl number.  It completes the existing PR_SET_THP_DISABLE flags
interface with the enable-side flag for scenario (4), in the encoding
that commit already reserved (bit 0 of the PR_GET_THP_DISABLE return
value is the disable state, higher bits are flags).

The emulation blessed by that commit -- handle (4) through (3), i.e.
set the global policy to "always" and have everything that should stay
at "madvise" opt out via PR_THP_DISABLE_EXCEPT_ADVISED -- is backwards
for this deployment shape.  On a handheld (or any fleet node) where
exactly one process should be elevated, it requires modifying every
OTHER process on the system to opt out: init, system daemons,
third-party services -- most of which cannot be modified, which is the
very premise that motivates the prctl approach in the first place.
The natural encoding of "one process opts in" is a flag on that one
process.  As for the alternative that commit deferred to, the
BPF-based per-process THP policy direction was subsequently set aside
by the community (LSFMM 2026), so there is no imminent replacement
interface for this to collide with.

In essence, this patch:

(A) Adds PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED, to be used as a flag in arg3 of
    prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE) when not disabling (arg2 == 0):

      prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE, 0, PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED, 0, 0);

    meaning: THPs are not disabled for this process and, additionally,
    every THP-eligible anonymous VMA in this mm is treated as if
    madvise(MADV_HUGEPAGE) had been called on it (MMF_THP_ALWAYS).
    Combining the flag with any disable mode (arg2 != 0) fails with
    -EINVAL: disabling THPs and treating unadvised VMAs as advised are
    mutually exclusive by construction, mirroring how
    PR_THP_DISABLE_EXCEPT_ADVISED is only accepted when disabling.

(B) Keeps prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE, 0, 0, 0, 0) as plain "back to
    default": it clears the disable modes exactly as before and now
    also clears MMF_THP_ALWAYS.  Existing callers observe no change,
    since they cannot have MMF_THP_ALWAYS set.

(C) Makes setting any disable mode (arg2 != 0) clear MMF_THP_ALWAYS.
    Both vma_thp_always() consumers sit behind the vma_thp_disabled()
    vetoes anyway, so a disable mode already overrides the hint in
    effect; clearing the bit as well keeps PR_GET_THP_DISABLE
    reporting a single coherent state ("disable always wins").

(D) Makes prctl(PR_GET_THP_DISABLE) return PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED (4)
    when the hint is set (and, per (C), no disable mode is).

    Encoding rationale: the merged interface reserved bit 0 for the
    disable state precisely so GET could return "1 | flags"; this
    extends the same scheme to "0 | flags".  A return of 0 still
    means "pure default", and "value & 1" remains the documented "is
    disabled" test.  The residual hazard is a legacy caller that
    tests the whole return value != 0 as "disabled": such a caller
    can only be confused inside a process that -- or whose launcher
    -- explicitly opted into PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED; for every process
    not using the new flag the returned values are bit-for-bit
    unchanged.  We chose this over reporting nothing (no
    introspection for the new mode) or gating the report behind a
    selector argument (a second calling convention for one bit of
    state).

One mm flag suffices because both halves of MADV_HUGEPAGE's behaviour
already key off the same two per-VMA predicates:

 1. Eligibility: thp_vma_allowable_orders() ORs in the madvise (and,
    under enabled=madvise, the inherit) order mask when the VMA is
    hinted.  Extend the hint test with vma_thp_always().

 2. Allocation effort: vma_thp_gfp_mask() gives a hinted VMA under
    the default defrag=madvise the bit-for-bit defrag=always mask
    (synchronous compaction, no __GFP_NORETRY under defrag=always).
    Extend vma_madvised with the same test.

Both tests share the vma_thp_always() helper, which is itself gated on
vma_is_anonymous(): the hint is anon-gated at the helper, so the
anon-only scope covers both consumers -- including the
vma_thp_gfp_mask() callers on shmem and swap-in paths that never go
through the anonymous-VMA eligibility check.

Precedence is conservative: the hint is applied where VM_HUGEPAGE
would be, and the vetoes are evaluated afterwards, so per-VMA
MADV_NOHUGEPAGE, global "never" and both PR_SET_THP_DISABLE modes
still win.  In particular the hint deliberately does NOT count as
"advised" for MMF_DISABLE_THP_EXCEPT_ADVISED -- with (C) the
combination cannot even be constructed via prctl(), and the veto
ordering backstops any future path that sets the bits directly.  A
stricter combined semantic can be relaxed later; the reverse is
UAPI-breaking.

The flag is inherited across fork() and exec(), matching
MMF_DISABLE_THP_*, so a launcher can prctl() and exec the target.
MMF_THP_ALWAYS sits above the legacy flags word, so mm_init()
propagates it explicitly rather than via MMF_INIT_LEGACY_MASK.
Unlike DISABLE, inheritance here inflates rather than restricts
resource use, so it can flow into an exec'd helper (or setuid
binary) that never asked for it; this is kept for symmetry with
THP_DISABLE and documented -- a launcher should set the flag as late
as possible, and children may clear it or use MADV_NOHUGEPAGE, both
of which are honoured.

The feature is 64-bit only (PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED is rejected with
-EINVAL on 32-bit and every flag read is gated on
IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_64BIT)), anon-only, and default-off: every
behavioural change is behind a flag test that is false for every
existing mm, so unflagged processes see zero policy change.  The
64-bit gate is a policy choice, not a mechanical constraint
(NUM_MM_FLAG_BITS is 64 on every architecture, so the bitmap could
hold the bit): no 32-bit use case has been identified and the feature
is untested there, and rejecting the flag today can be relaxed later
without breaking UAPI, whereas retracting 32-bit support could not be.
/proc/pid/status THP_enabled is unchanged: it keeps reporting only the
complete-disable state, exactly as before.

Note on standalone effect, measured honestly: this patch alone was
neutral on the motivating workload.  On-fault THP only covers
mappings faulted after the flag is set, and stock khugepaged (10 s
scan interval, small round-robin budget) never caught up with the
already-faulted heap within a ~67 s benchmark run.  The follow-up
patch adds the khugepaged promptness that makes the flag deliver; the
interface and the collapse prioritization are kept separate so each
can be reviewed on its own terms.

Signed-off-by: David Vernet <void@manifault.com>
